Today is the deadline specified in the opposition's ultimatum to Lukashenko. Since he is unlikely to leave the office, tomorrow we should see nationwide strikes in Belarus. I think however that with only less than 17 days left to the end of our forecasted period, the probability of new wave of protests success that fast is very low. Especially since very big demonstrations and strikes were not able to succeed before. I admire courageous people of Belarus who oppose the totalitarian regime, but with the loyalty of the army, KGB and police forces and the backing form Putin (recent visit of Russian chief of intelligence in Minsk might be another sign of cooperation and support, maybe even preparations for opposition actions) they bravery might not be enough even if the whole country would become a prison and the whole nation would become prisoners.

"On the final day of what Belarus's opposition has called the 'People's Ultimatum' — a demand that President Alexander Lukashenko resign or face a nationwide strike — tens of thousands of protesters marched in Minsk on Sunday before police cracked down with stun grenades ... The ultimatum was issued two weeks ago by [Svetlana Tikhanovskaya], the main opposition candidate ... Lukashenko has given no indication that he is amenable to Tikhanovskaya’s terms, and it’s unclear whether Belarusians will heed her call for a strike." https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/after-lukashenko-ignores-ultimatum-deadline-belarusian-opposition-leader-calls-for-nationwide-strike/2020/10/25/3a96a622-16e0-11eb-82db-60b15c874105_story.html

Opposition party leader wanted by Russian government, protesters have been brutalized and locked up, international media has been kicked out and silenced, and protests have diminished in both size and frequency. With just 3 weeks left until the deadline for this question, he would essentially need to die to cease to be President. He's in his 60s and heavily guarded so this doesn't seem very plausible within the next month.

I would say that probably less than 1% now with 26 days to the end date and no visible source of real change (the main potential source of change are People of Belarus but now it seems that they are stuck), but there is still some uncertainty (unknown unknowns), and 99% chance of remaining when you have almost the whole nation against you is pretty high. Who would forecasted Cleon I fate? Yes, the base rate was against him. Yes, that was an Isaac Asimov's fiction, but still good for imagination - unknown unknown - let's say a girlfriend of one of his bodyguards was killed by OMON walking home, and KGB did not connect the dots in time... or a heart attack, stroke or a helicopter crash - tiny risk accumulating - the total risk is not high especially given this 26 days but I am not comfortable with 100%. I like to think about probability as in the simulation of multiple worlds with slight differences - if we run the simulation 100 times then only in 1 of 100 worlds he is no longer a president before 11 November.

"Exiled Belarusian opposition leader Sviatlana Tsikhanouskaya set an Oct. 25 deadline on Tuesday for President Alexander Lukashenko to quit or face nationwide strikes that would paralyse the country ... Tsikhanouskaya expected the West to support her demands, the aide said." https://www.reuters.com/article/us-belarus-election-ultimatum-idUSKBN26Y1KP

Lukashenko’s position has been further strengthened by the actions of the EU. Using political tactics known as ‘pork barrelling’ in the U.S. Cyprus has vetoed sanctions addressed Lukashenko until the EU takes actions against Turkey for offshore drilling. Only sanctions against Belarusian officials will be forthcoming. Lukashenko can dismiss any EU threats and remain in power as long as it suits Russia. https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/oct/02/belarus-officials-eu-sanctions-lukashenko

Lukashenko, against all the odds, has held onto the loyalty of the OMON and military and Belarusian KGB who will be watching Russia for any signs to switch to another side. Therefore, the power remains with the Kremlin. The falling of Lukashenko will give proof to the idea that street protests can be successful which is not an agreeable solution to those in power and possibly give him more time to consolidate his position. His other advantage is the lack of a discernible opposition on the ground in Belarus. Tikhanovskaya’s tours of European capitals have little effect, given the EU is somewhat ineffectual when confronting Belarus/Russia and demonstrators are not pro-western but anti-Lukashenko. The only peaceful solution will be the quiet (if possible) replacement of an apparatchik of the current administration and a toning down of the police violence.

Outside of some very low probability random event I belive only Putin or Lukashenko own men can took the power from him. Putin seems to be using weakend Lukashenko as an oportunity. I have also read about the purges Lukashenko regulary conducted among his supporters including KGB - it seem rather unlikely that as the situation is now (seem to be rather under control by the regime) someone would successfully remove him from power by that date.

Just under a month and a half before this date and the headlines have died down, his main opposition is still in another country, and he has shown 0 interest in stepping down. No large players have emerged to force his hand and the majority of protests have been either disbanded or put down with force. Hard to see how he will cease to be President beyond an extreme event (sudden death, assassination, etc.) which are historically unlikely even given the unrest in the region.
Dictators generally fall due to widespread economic discontent + Belarus looks set to be go on a second wave = not insignificant chance of fall (short time frame goes against though)
Another factor is that the ruble is weaker now.

The opposition does not have a focal point or any inclination to take over buildings or mount the barricades and so is easily contained. The demonstrations remain passive (except for the forced removal of balaclavas), while the security forces are increasing the detaining of civilians and violence against the demonstrators. Russia will be concerned given the similar demonstrations in Russia's Far East, Khabarovsk (using free Belarus placards) that will not help. Lukashenko will only be removed by the persuasion of the Kremlin and replaced with a more pliable individual. Any action from the EU or others is probably being ignored.

I am going to stay higher on this. The protest are not abating despite the arrests. Putin does not want to turn the Belarus population against him. No mass shootings so far. His support for Lukashenko might shift to someone else taking over and then a staged election. The vote might be fair but only Pro Putin candidates allowed. Only Putin knows for sure. https://www.politico.eu/article/why-putin-hasnt-won-the-game-in-belarus/

The continued peaceful protests may have some effect but it is more likely there would be another election rather than his just resigning. Russia cannot afford to let him fall.

Hi @hughie33, reading your comment and the forecast I think you have misread the question - it is "...will Alexander Lukashenko CEASE to be the president of Belarus?" not "...will Alexander Lukashenko BE the president of Belarus?". Also think about your Score - do not give 100% just to effect the community forecast you don't agree with. Good luck!
Protests are on a downtrend

"The Kremlin's immediate priority seems to be in stabilising the situation across the border, trying to keep brotherly Belarus, broadly, in Moscow's orbit and making sure disgruntled Russians do not get any ideas about the effectiveness of mass protests ... For now, at least, that means public backing for the man those protesters have turned on and who is now busy positioning himself as the most loyal friend Moscow could have ... So Mr Putin held out a $1.5bn (£1.2bn) credit line that will help Alexander Lukashenko pay the wages of the security forces keeping him in place - amongst other things ... critically, he confirmed that Russia would stand by all commitments to its neighbour including the promise of reinforcements should events on the ground deteriorate ... But behind the scenes, some believe Russian support for the long-time ruler of Belarus is more qualified, even that the Kremlin believes he is now a liability it can no longer trust, fatally weakened by the protests and unable to deliver on any major promises." https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54155882

Seems to have Putin's backing and not heard much about protests in the news. Now that he's survived the immediate backlash it's difficult to see him falling. Interesting thought from others that perhaps Putin will still try and replace him behind the scenes - this is possible but perhaps unlikely in the short term.
POTUS has demonstrated a hands off policy WRT what Russia is doing. Lukashenko's future is closely linked to Putin who has already spoke in support of his Byelorussian beauty.

Putin is not moving to directly crush dissent. He may try to get rid of Lukashenko behind the scenes. https://www.cbsnews.com/news/russia-vladimir-putin-belarus-alexander-lukashenko-protests-must-be-resolved-without-interference/

Despite the size of the rally over the weekend (1), I don't think a peaceful protest will result in the Lukashenko stepping down. With cash and support from Russia (2), and the promise of the a change to the constitution (3), I can't see this pathway ending his reign this year.
Dumb liberal protesters don't realize Lukashenko will Make Belarus Great Again.
Lukashenko is meeting with Putin
Reducing my estimate of the chance Lukashenko is no longer president by November 11 in response to recent moves by Putin to support him.

Putin cannot afford for the protesters to win since that could be a bad inspiration for the Russian people in the future - they might start to think: if anti-presidential protests would succeed in Belarus why not in Russia? So he must either support Lukashenko to stay in power at least till the end of the protests or he must replace him but then it would have to look like not the success of protests. It is impossible for me to imagine all the possibilities but one way for Putin to replace Lukashenko and do not make it look like protesters succeded is to make him "die from a heart attack" or something - but this would be quite a radical move and Putin would probably need the support of some current key Lukashenko's backers - I am not sure if they would be ready just yet to turn on him. Replacement of Lukashenko could be benefitial for Putin in longer term if he play his cards well - he could in fact get much more control over Belarus (thru investment of money, activity of his secret services and criminal groups he control) but there is also a risk. I think his is not that comfortable with backing Lukashenko, but he might continue to do so untill the price is to high. In the same time he probably is preparing for other options. For now he could really pressure Lukashenko to try to gain what he wanted for a long time since Lukashenko is now so dependent of his support.
He won’t give up willingly and there is no real challenge from the opposition protestors. A general strike or external pressure might change things but as of now he is not going anywhere.

Monday we will see if AL is offered a cup of tea or a dacha in Sochi or a glass of Vodka with the generals. Putin may insist on a closer union in return for assitance. A closer union would offer a real excuse for a Belarus constitutional change, something AL has insisted is needed before proceeding. A closer union may come with initial economic incentives as recognition of Belarus importance. An updated constitution coupled with economic incentives may divide the opposition demonstrators. And winter is coming, not a good time to stand in the streets.

The rationale behind this forecast is as follows: A) the political support Lukashenko presently enjoys from at least Putin appears to be enough to stave off direct/military international intervention (e.g. UN) in Belarus before 11 November 2020; B) the United States (the only nation reasonably most able to directly intervene in Belarus) has not shown any appetite on the issue; C) it's likely that Lukashenko will outweigh internal resistance by continuing to employ violence of the state (e.g. police, military, etc.) to hold onto power; and D) the humanitarian/political/social situation in Belarus (albeit distasteful) likely hasn't reached the level to which the international community (e.g. UN) would be moved to directly intervene, or challenge Putin's support of Lukashenko's regime.
Putin is backing him. Old KGB doesn't have problems they create them. While Lukashenko is of value to the Kremlin, he will remain in power.
Cutting in half, no positive news.

Dropping probability significantly as it looks like the people on the street may not have enough momentum to see this through by Nov 11.

The bouncing ball follows the snippets of news from Belarus. The notion made by AL that another election could happen shows the depth of the rebellion. With little news assessing the outcome in 2 months is just too difficult. Russia could easily replace him. A fresh election would draw the attention of the EU. Most likely, AL will become ill and retire to Sochi and a hand picked Russian friendly person will assume the leadership.

AL is picking off the opposition leaders one by one "old style". AL won't be gone unless Russia replaces him with someone. This is still a real possibility, just not at the moment. When AL visits Russia next week we may see a new turn of events.
At this point, Lukashenko seems entrenched. I don't think things will settle down anytime soon, but I don't think Lukashenko will lose power before November 11th.
With Russia's backing and the Trump administration sticking to "America First", it is highly doubtful anything will happen until after January 2021...if even then.

Lukashenko has Russia's backing, and I think there's a zero percent chance the western world will give the Belarusian people enough aid to oust him; especially not by the 11th of November. That's my reason...as an experiment I would like to see the Belarusians try a peaceful revolution. I've had this idea for a while - the people and corporations (in any state) could dump all their currency into various cryptos, esp. the ones designed for stability (like DAI). Stores could start accepting crypto etc, and everyone quits paying taxes. If say 50% of the population did this, could the regime manage it? I doubt it...I think it would be a substantial blow to their power and the movement would grow. With the regime eventually having a shortage of resources for any king of war, foreign countries might intervene to establish some kind of stability.
This guy ain't leaving any time soon.

While Russian support for Lukashenko does appear strong, with Putin offering military intervention, it is also conceivable that Moscow may make a deal with elites in security services to put someone more friendly to them in power.

Cutting by factor of ten, it appears that AL has kept the old apparatus in place and Russia has added more. There appear to be two factions, one wanting to replace AL and the other wanting to amend the constitution - this could be the ending of the beginning.

"Tens of thousands of people marched through Minsk on Sunday calling on Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko to step down, in mass demonstrations that showed no sign of abating nearly a month after an election his opponents say was rigged ... Lukashenko has been in power since 1994 and, buoyed by a show of support from traditional ally Russia, has rejected calls for new elections from Sviatlana Tsikhanouskaya, his main opponent who fled into exile two days after the vote." https://www.reuters.com/article/us-belarus-election/belarus-protesters-march-in-minsk-despite-government-warning-idUSKBN25X0L8

Additionally, with Trump suggesting that German's findings on the assassination attempt of Navalny may be incorrect, effectively siding with Russia, it is unlikely the US will support any international efforts to depose AL. Externally, Russia is quite a confounding factor: though Lukashenko refuted Putin’s suggestion of a country merge in the past, Putin has a vested interest in showing force towards both NATO and his own protestors by sending troops into Belarus as a demonstration of support for the regime. However, increased protests within his own country, as well as everything happening in Belarus, may have rattled Putin (if the suspected poisoning of Alexei Navalny is any indication); he seems aware of the counterproductive nature of police brutality as a tool to suppress dissent. Furthermore, given the economic union between Russia and Belarus, any future Belarusian government would likely still be reliant on Russia: thus, Putin may have no particular political incentive to help Lukashenko that much. In the West, both the EU and the US have refused to recognize the legitimacy of Belarus’s recent election, but response beyond that has been feeble: some sanctions were called for in the EU, but nothing more. It appears that this issue will most likely be settled domestically: the one thing that is clear is the fact that Lukashenko needs the loyalty of his own security forces and armies to stay in power. If the protests of the Belarusian people continue in their current scope, he may find himself losing this loyalty; the question is whether he will lose it before November.

Regime changes originating in protests/riots are extremely rare events. ACLED Data globally shows about 1000 protests annually where the government is the target (proxied by "police force" in the data, while this annual rate is likely to be much higher because the number of protests without this filter is in tens of thousands). Data on coup d'etat usually show 5-10 events per year (see Wiki). While this is not the only way to change regime, it proxies well 'forceful ousting', which would be the most conceivable way of Lukashenko leaving before November 11 currently. So the quantitative base for Lukashenko being ousted is very low, moving around 1%-5% (with some exaggeration). Accordingly, the "CoupCast" predictive tool assessed the August 2020 chance of coup occurring in Belarus to 0.7% (fairly high, comparable to many countries in the global south, but one would still not bet on a "yes").

Upping my forecast for several reasons. 1) As noted by multiple comments, Russia is not backing Lukashenko as fervently as many would have initially suspected. While this could change, Russia's willingness to distance itself undermines the credibility of Lukashenko on an international stage even further and is more likely to spur external, open support for his removal. 2) The protests are growing, not shrinking. In my initial post, I suggested that it was likely the protests would begin to die down as time passed, but recent reports suggest the exact opposite. This not only shows that the people of Belarus are intent on making a change and willing to fight for it despite reports of the arrests and abuse of protesters, but their prolonged protests are bringing further international attention. 3) Similarly, the news cycle has not yet grown bored of this story which, unfortunately, is surprising but promising for those that want Lukashenko out. More news means more information for everyday citizens, which means more outrage both at home and abroad, which means more pressure on political leaders and dissidents to throw Lukashenko out of office. Whether this happens by November 11th is still up in the air, especially with everything going on and the possibility the story does begin being buried under an ever changing news cycle, but right now is as likely a time as any for a head of state to be thrown from (or flee) their office.

Lushashenko has held the presidency for almost three decades. In that time, he has been able to consolidate almost all governing power under himself, either directly or through surrogates in the legislative and judicial branches of Belarus. Even if these two branches were to turn on him, he still wields more power than either of them, including an ability to simply dissolve the House of Representatives, appoint (and therefore dismiss) nearly all judges, and name eight members to the upper house. So, legislatively, it is virtually impossible to force him to quit the presidency via impeachment or similar means. As for public opinion, polls are heavily regulated, with the most recent ones (2016) leaked to outside news outlets showing an approval lingering around 30%, very low for such a long-serving leader. Moreover, he has blamed these protests on criminals and unemployment, telling people to 'get a job' instead of addressing the electoral fraud questions directly. There also appears to be little to no outside pressure from any foreign power for his resignation, while many foreign authoritarians are voicing their support for him. As such, it is unlikely he will step down due to public or international pressure, as he does not appear to believe the people's support is a priority and has no reason to fear foreign interference. So, that really only leaves a successful assassination attempt. In the last 20 years, there have only been five successful assassinations of heads of state, with the last coming in 2011 with the death of Gaddafi. So a decent anchor rate is 25% per year, or 6.25% per 3 months. As no foreign powers have taken an interest in his removal (so far), this should be lowered. Let's say 4%. Now, the election results were only announced on August 9th, so while large protests are not a good thing for the president, until they become long-term they are unlikely to represent any sustained and organized threat to his seat or his life. It will be interesting to see if these demonstrations continue (or even increase) in the coming weeks, in which case the percentage may begin creeping up to mirror the added intensity and seriousness of sustained and widespread displeasure.
